b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\n\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC " -//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\n<workbook_page id="p2_enthalpy_comb" xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\n    xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\n    xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\n    xmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/">\n\n\n    <head>\n        <title>Enthalpy of Combustion</title>\n        <objref idref="enthalpy"/>\n    </head>\n\n    <body>\n        <section>\n            <title>Enthalpy Changes at Standard State</title>\n            <body>\n                \n                \n                <p> Enthalpy changes are typically tabulated for reactions in which both the\n                    reactants and products are at the same conditions. A standard state is a\n                    commonly accepted set of conditions used as a reference point for the\n                    determination of properties under other different conditions. For chemists, the\n                    IUPAC standard state refers to materials under a pressure of 1 bar and solutions\n                    at 1 M, and does not specify a temperature. Many thermochemical tables list\n                    values with a standard state of 1 atm. Because the \xce\x94<em style="italic">H</em> of\n                    a reaction changes very little with such small changes in pressure (1 bar =\n                    0.987 atm), \xce\x94<em style="italic">H</em> values (except for the most precisely\n                    measured values) are essentially the same under both sets of standard\n                    conditions. We will include a superscripted \xe2\x80\x9co\xe2\x80\x9d in the enthalpy change symbol to\n                    designate standard state. Since the usual (but not technically standard)\n                    temperature is 298.15 K, we will use a subscripted \xe2\x80\x9c298\xe2\x80\x9d to designate this\n                    temperature. Thus, the symbol <m:math display="inline">\n                        <m:mrow>\n                            <m:mi>&Delta;</m:mi>\n                            <m:msubsup>\n                                <m:mi>H</m:mi>\n                                <m:mtext>298</m:mtext>\n                                <m:mtext>o</m:mtext>\n                            </m:msubsup>\n                        </m:mrow>\n                    </m:math> is used to indicate an enthalpy change for a process occurring under\n                    these conditions. (The symbol \xce\x94<em style="italic">H</em> is used to indicate an\n                    enthalpy change for a reaction occurring under nonstandard conditions.) </p>\n                <p>The enthalpy changes for many types of chemical and physical processes are\n                    available in the reference literature, including those for combustion reactions,\n                    phase transitions, and formation reactions. As we discuss these quantities, it\n                    is important to pay attention to the extensive nature of enthalpy and enthalpy\n                    changes. Since the enthalpy change for a given reaction is proportional to the\n                    amounts of substances involved, it may be reported on that basis (i.e., as the\n                    \xce\x94<em style="italic">H</em> for specific amounts of reactants). However, we\n                    often find it more useful to divide one extensive property (\xce\x94<em style="italic"\n                        >H</em>) by another (amount of substance), and report a per-amount intensive\n                    value of \xce\x94<em style="italic">H</em>, often \xe2\x80\x9cnormalized\xe2\x80\x9d to a per-mole basis.\n                    (Note that this is similar to determining the intensive property specific heat\n                    from the extensive property heat capacity, as seen previously.)</p>\n                \n            </body>\n            \n        </section>\n<section>\n    <title>Standard Enthalpy of Combustion</title>\n    <body>\n        <p>Standard enthalpy of combustion (<m:math display="inline">\n                <m:mrow>\n                    <m:mi>&Delta;</m:mi>\n                    <m:msubsup>\n                        <m:mi>H</m:mi>\n                        <m:mtext>C</m:mtext>\n                        <m:mtext>o</m:mtext>\n                    </m:msubsup>\n                </m:mrow>\n            </m:math> ) is the enthalpy change when 1 mole of a substance burns (combines vigorously\n            with oxygen) under standard state conditions; it is sometimes called \xe2\x80\x9cheat of\n            combustion.\xe2\x80\x9d For example, the enthalpy of combustion of ethanol, \xe2\x88\x921366.8 kJ/mol, is the\n            amount of heat produced when one mole of ethanol undergoes complete combustion at 25 \xc2\xb0C\n            and 1 atmosphere pressure, yielding products also at 25 \xc2\xb0C and 1 atm. </p>\n        <formula>\n            <m:math display="block">\n                <m:mrow>\n                    <m:msub>\n                        <m:mtext>C</m:mtext>\n                        <m:mtext>2</m:mtext>\n                    </m:msub>\n                    <m:msub>\n                        <m:mtext>H</m:mtext>\n                        <m:mtext>5</m:mtext>\n                    </m:msub>\n                    <m:mtext>OH(</m:mtext>\n                    <m:mi>l</m:mi>\n                    <m:mtext>) + 3</m:mtext>\n                    <m:msub>\n                        <m:mtext>O</m:mtext>\n                        <m:mn>2</m:mn>\n                    </m:msub>\n                    <m:mtext>(</m:mtext>\n                    <m:mi>g</m:mi>\n                    <m:mtext fontfamily="Times New Roman">) &nbsp;</m:mtext>\n                    <m:mo lspace="3px" rspace="3px">&rarr;</m:mo>\n                    <m:mtext>2 C</m:mtext>\n                    <m:msub>\n                        <m:mtext>O</m:mtext>\n                        <m:mn>2</m:mn>\n                    </m:msub>\n                    <m:mtext>(</m:mtext>\n                    <m:mi>g</m:mi>\n                    <m:mtext>) + 3</m:mtext>\n                    <m:msub>\n                        <m:mtext>H</m:mtext>\n                        <m:mn>2</m:mn>\n                    </m:msub>\n                    <m:mtext>O(</m:mtext>\n                    <m:mi>l</m:mi>\n                    <m:mtext>)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \xce\x94</m:mtext>\n                    <m:msubsup>\n                        <m:mi>H</m:mi>\n                        <m:mi>C</m:mi>\n                        <m:mi>o</m:mi>\n                    </m:msubsup>\n                    <m:mtext>= \xe2\x88\x921366.8 kJ</m:mtext>\n                </m:mrow>\n            </m:math>\n        </formula>\n        <p>Enthalpies of combustion for many substances have been measured; a few of these are\n            listed in the table below. Many readily available substances with large enthalpies of\n            combustion are used as fuels, including hydrogen, carbon (as coal or charcoal), and\n            hydrocarbons (compounds containing only hydrogen and carbon), such as methane, propane,\n            and the major components of gasoline.</p>\n        <table>\n            <title>Enthalpy of Combustion in kJ/mol at 25\xc2\xb0C</title>\n            <tr>\n                <td>\n                    <em>Substance</em>\n                </td>\n                <td>\n                    <em>Combustion Reaction</em>\n                </td>\n                <td>\n                    <m:math display="block">\n                        <m:mrow>\n                            <m:mtext>\xce\x94</m:mtext>\n                            <m:msubsup>\n                                <m:mi>H</m:mi>\n                                <m:mi>C</m:mi>\n                                <m:mi>o</m:mi>\n                            </m:msubsup>\n                        </m:mrow>\n                    </m:math>\n                </td>\n            </tr>\n            <tr>\n                <td> carbon </td>\n                <td> C(s) + O<sub>2</sub>(g)\xe2\x9f\xb6 CO<sub>2</sub>(g) </td>\n                <td> \xe2\x88\x92393.5 </td>\n            </tr>\n            <tr>\n                <td>hydrogen</td>\n\n                <td>H<sub>2</sub>(g) + 1/2 O<sub>2</sub>(g) \xe2\x9f\xb6 H<sub>2</sub>O(l)</td>\n\n                <td>\xe2\x88\x92285.8</td>\n            </tr>\n            <tr>\n                <td>magnesium</td>\n\n                <td>Mg(s) + 1/2 O<sub>2</sub>(g) \xe2\x9f\xb6 MgO(s)</td>\n\n                <td>\xe2\x88\x92601.6</td>\n            </tr>\n            <tr>\n                <td>sulfur</td>\n\n                <td>S(s) + O<sub>2</sub>(g) \xe2\x9f\xb6 SO<sub>2</sub>(g)</td>\n\n                <td>\xe2\x88\x92296.8 </td>\n            </tr>\n            <tr>\n                <td>carbon monoxide</td>\n\n                <td>CO(g) + 1/2 O<sub>2</sub>(g) \xe2\x9f\xb6 CO<sub>2</sub>(g)</td>\n\n                <td>\xe2\x88\x92283.0</td>\n            </tr>\n            <tr>\n                <td>methane</td>\n\n                <td>CH<sub>4</sub>(g) + 2 O<sub>2</sub>(g) \xe2\x9f\xb6 CO<sub>2</sub>(g) + 2\n                    H<sub>2</sub>O(l)</td>\n\n                <td>\xe2\x88\x92890.8</td>\n            </tr>\n            <tr>\n                <td>acetylene</td>\n\n                <td>C<sub>2</sub>H<sub>2</sub>(g) + 5/2 O<sub>2</sub>(g) \xe2\x9f\xb62 CO<sub>2</sub>(g) + 2\n                        H<sub>2</sub>O(l)</td>\n\n                <td>\xe2\x88\x921301.1</td>\n            </tr>\n            <tr>\n                <td>ethanol</td>\n\n                <td> C<sub>2</sub>H<sub>5</sub>OH(l) + 3 O<sub>2</sub>(g) \xe2\x9f\xb62 CO<sub>2</sub>(g) + 3\n                        H<sub>2</sub>O(l)</td>\n\n                <td>\xe2\x88\x921366.8</td>\n            </tr>\n            <tr>\n                <td>methanol</td>\n\n                <td>CH<sub>3</sub>OH(l) + 3/2 O2(g) \xe2\x9f\xb6 CO<sub>2</sub>(g) + 2 H<sub>2</sub>O(l)</td>\n\n                <td>\xe2\x88\x92726.1</td>\n            </tr>\n            <tr>\n                <td>isooctane</td>\n\n                <td> C<sub>8</sub>H<sub>18</sub>(l) + 25/2 O<sub>2</sub>(g) \xe2\x9f\xb68 CO<sub>2</sub>(g) + 9\n                        H<sub>2</sub>O(l)</td>\n\n                <td> \xe2\x88\x925461</td>\n            </tr>\n        </table>\n        <example>\n            <p>As seen in the image below, the combustion of gasoline is a highly exothermic\n                process. Let us determine the approximate amount of heat produced by burning 1.00 L\n                of gasoline, assuming the enthalpy of combustion of gasoline is the same as that of\n                isooctane, a common component of gasoline. The density of isooctane is 0.692\n                g/mL.</p>\n            <image src="../webcontent/fire_image.jpg" alt="A picture shows a large ball of fire burning on a road. A fire truck and fireman are shown in the foreground.\n                ">\n                <caption> The combustion of gasoline is very exothermic. (credit: modification of work by \xe2\x80\x9cAlexEagle\xe2\x80\x9d/Flickr)</caption>\n            </image>\n            <p>Starting with a known amount (1.00 L of isooctane), we can perform conversions\n                between units until we arrive at the desired amount of heat or energy. The enthalpy\n                of combustion of isooctane provides one of the necessary conversions. The table\n                above gives this value as \xe2\x88\x925460 kJ per 1 mole of isooctane\n                    (C<sub>8</sub>H<sub>18</sub>).</p>\n            <formula>$$\\require{cancel} 1.00\\cancel{\\;\\mathrm L\\;{\\mathrm C}_8{\\mathrm\n                H}_{18}}\\;\\times\\;\\frac{1000\\cancel{\\;\\mathrm{mL}\\;{\\mathrm C}_8{\\mathrm\n                H}_{18}}}{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm L\\;{\\mathrm C}_8{\\mathrm\n                H}_{18}}}\\times\\;\\frac{0.692\\cancel{\\;\\mathrm g\\;{\\mathrm C}_8{\\mathrm\n                H}_{18}}}{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mL}\\;{\\mathrm C}_8{\\mathrm\n                H}_{18}}}\\times\\frac{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm C}_8{\\mathrm\n                H}_{18}}}{114\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm g\\;{\\mathrm C}_8{\\mathrm\n                H}_{18}}}\\times\\frac{-5460\\;\\mathrm{kJ}}{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm\n                C}_8{\\mathrm H}_{18}}}=\\;-3.31\\times10^4\\;\\mathrm{kJ}$$ </formula>\n            <p>The combustion of 1.00 L of isooctane produces 33,100 kJ of heat. (This is alot of\n                energy; it is enough to melt 99.2 kg, or about 218 lbs, of ice.) </p>\n        </example>\n\n        <wb:inline idref="enthalpy_comb_lbd1" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\n\n        <wb:inline idref="enthalpy_comb_digt1" purpose="didigetthis"/>\n    </body>\n</section>\n    </body>\n</workbook_page>\n'